I. Pavlov was an unbelievably intellectual man. He was conscious of the full implications of his ideas and also didn't think in terms of crude mechanical conditioning, but an "exploration reflex", alertness, and volition. Consciousness as a situation or goal-directed interaction.

The basic concept that life is based on contextual feedback and constantly adapting to novelty. If people actually study the Pavlov school of physiology, it would ironically end the idiocy the culture has developed around the dog experiment. It's all #FunctionalPerformanceSystems

One of the most evocative texts I've read is a 14th century Orthodox manuscript about a 9th century Bulgarian soldier, who had his horse's leg break in the middle of battle when purused, and prayed to God and St. George for help, after which the horse's leg immediately recovered.

Everyone else in his corps was slaughtered, but he escaped. After that he says he got to his home, where while he was lying down with his wife, he saw a "clean-shaven, radiant" man, who appeared in front of him and introduced himself as St. George, who saved his life in that war.

He told him that the horse will die in a few days and to see its leg, which turned out to have the bone held together by three metal rings that miraculously had appeared there. Imagine you're lying down on the couch with your gf and a saint just materializes in your living room.

The other day on the street, I noticed someone had a gait similar to Putin. I thought about what if Putin decided to imitate his own gain. He would produce something else. What if he then decided to imitate that (Putin imitating Putin's gait gait). Infinity. I screamed in horror.

Hoisting an object in front of your torso and tracking it with your eyes alone, especially if you move it towards the side of whatever hand you hold it with, is a powerful gesture. One does that to animals to control their attention absolutely, that's how you hypnotize chickens.

But doing it on your own to yourself implies a fascination with one's own actions, observing yourself from inside as a second person would, an implied mirror, action-as-mirror, it is playfulness and a truly primordial innocence, one imagines Adam would do that in Eden before Fall
Bacchus, Michaelangelo, look at the eyes fascinated by his own creation, the eyes are fully tilted to the right even if the neck does not follow

There is no ultimate Putin gait, just as how a polygon resembles a circle more and more as it approaches having infinite sides but can never become a circle, as Rene Guenon proves. The infinite perfect Putin gait would make mankind fall down in terror and astonishment before it.
